00:21:36,787 --> 00:21:39,392
So that's the other one of the taints, you know.

201
00:21:39,794 --> 00:21:46,163
if you remember, sensual desire, desire for existence, and ignorance.

202
00:21:46,785 --> 00:21:54,517
So all these lists, I think you just take them as indications, that's all, indications.

203
00:21:54,537 --> 00:21:58,923
So the best thing to get is the Buddhist Dictionary.

204
00:21:59,324 --> 00:22:00,526
Here we are, Buddhist Dictionary.

205
00:22:00,566 --> 00:22:02,789
Oh, you can't see it.

206
00:22:02,809 --> 00:22:06,596
The Buddhist Dictionary, a manual of Buddhist terms and doctrines by Jnana Tiloka.

207
00:22:06,996 --> 00:22:08,198
And he's got it all there for you.

208
00:22:08,464 --> 00:22:14,393
You get it from BPS, which is the Buddhist Publication Society in Kandy.

209
00:22:15,034 --> 00:22:17,757
I think you can download it as a PDF too.

210
00:22:17,836 --> 00:22:20,641
So that'll give you all your lists.

211
00:22:23,444 --> 00:22:24,385
How are we doing for time?

212
00:22:29,593 --> 00:22:31,234
Okay, it's getting on, isn't it?

213
00:22:31,255 --> 00:22:31,756
It's getting on.

214
00:22:34,900 --> 00:22:36,582
Oh yes, just the last one here.

215
00:22:37,928 --> 00:22:41,532
I also have some thoughts on assuming the position of the observer.

216
00:22:42,233 --> 00:22:45,116
I'm not good at staying with sensations for a long time.

217
00:22:45,678 --> 00:22:53,367
Rather, I'm at that stage of my development where it tends to last for a split second or so, maybe minutes in some circumstances.

218
00:22:53,468 --> 00:23:01,218
I gather from the Mahasi treaties that this state tends to extend itself with practice until liberation when it becomes permanent.

219
00:23:01,719 --> 00:23:05,083
The only exception seems to be, for me, meditating on pain.

220
00:23:05,619 --> 00:23:09,967
I work a lot with pain, provides a powerful focus.

221
00:23:10,929 --> 00:23:20,503
Eventually, and in the right circumstance, this focus leads to the objectivization of pain itself, once the position of the observer is established.

222
00:23:20,984 --> 00:23:24,329
This is also one of the most effective ways of managing pain, I find.

223
00:23:25,392 --> 00:23:28,978
Pity, it tends to be more impermanent than the pain itself.

224
00:23:30,426 --> 00:23:33,150
Yes, that's what we discover, isn't it?

225
00:23:33,611 --> 00:23:43,041
That with things that are unpleasant, when we have dealt with the reaction, see that's the important thing, not wanting to go there, feel the reaction.

226
00:23:43,643 --> 00:23:52,933
When the reaction goes and we then turn towards the difficulty, the pain, physical or mental, then we can stay with it.

227
00:23:53,074 --> 00:23:56,738
And of course, we realize that the reaction is causing the suffering.

228
00:23:57,173 --> 00:24:00,518
Pain is just pain, as it were, and we can be quite equanimous with it.

229
00:24:02,167 --> 00:24:20,672
Now, one thing I did that's brought to mind, which I didn't stress actually in the discussion yesterday evening about not-self, when I talked about the object, the distinction between the subject, the observer, the feeler, the knower, and what is felt, seen, observed, etc.

230
00:24:21,153 --> 00:24:28,362
You can make that clear to yourself by making the distance between the two obvious to yourself.

231
00:24:28,342 --> 00:24:54,180
so for instance if there's pain in the knee you're up here somewhere looking down and you can say there's there's pain so that's and then to to sort of uh be aware of the distance that there is between the two the observer and the observer so it's like here now you're looking at the screen and um at me no doubt and uh and i'm filling most of your awareness most of your attention

232
00:24:54,160 --> 00:24:59,156
Now, if you become aware of the distance between your eyes and the screen.

233
00:25:00,923 --> 00:25:06,583
Now, that's what I mean by recognizing the distinction between the subject and object.

234
00:25:07,036 --> 00:25:12,340
And you find you can do that with emotions because they're in the body and you're still up here.

235
00:25:12,902 --> 00:25:18,366
Images, sometimes you can see them ahead of you and you can at least intuit the space.

236
00:25:18,386 --> 00:25:20,670
There must be a space there between them, as it were.

237
00:25:20,950 --> 00:25:21,871
It's a mental space.

238
00:25:22,912 --> 00:25:24,212
Thoughts, of course, very difficult.

239
00:25:25,815 --> 00:25:33,162
And that again accentuates the whole business of what I'm experiencing

240
00:25:33,714 --> 00:25:36,359
doesn't constitute me, right?

241
00:25:36,380 --> 00:25:41,189
Because this me now is felt to be the observer, okay?

242
00:25:41,209 --> 00:25:44,275
So I think that's enough of that for one evening, don't you think?

243
00:25:45,155 --> 00:25:47,740
And we can begin our meditation.

244
00:25:47,961 --> 00:25:51,768
I just hope, as usual, that I've not caused even more confusion.

245
00:25:53,330 --> 00:25:53,731
Very good.

